"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391685","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-07","<p>No, given the rights and obligations of businesses holding stock on behalf of third parties are well-established and in the event of a dispute it is for the courts to determine the outcome, based on the facts of the case.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-09-07T08:42:37.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391685/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391685/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Electronic Commerce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will bring forward regulations to clarify the legal protections that third party companies receive with regard to stock and stock lists which are held by online retailers; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","8232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391686","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-08","<p>The Balance of Competence Review, published in July 2014, said that costs would dramatically rise if the flexibility afforded by the individual opt-out were no longer available. Respondents to the Balance of Competence Review’s Call for Evidence felt that the ECJ judgments surrounding on-call working, accrual and carry-over of annual leave as well as payment for annual leave posed further significant costs.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-09-08T15:49:16.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391686/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391686/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391686/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Working Hours: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the cost to the British economy of the EU Working Time Directive in the most recent year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","8197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391687","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Government protected the science ring-fence in cash terms for financial year 2015/16 at £4.6bn. In addition the Chancellor announced in December 2014 a long-term commitment to investment in science infrastructure at £1.1bn per annum in real terms to 2021.</p><p>Decisions on the amount and allocation of funding beyond 2015/16 will be made as part of the Spending Review. We cannot pre-judge the Spending Review outcome.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","8264","2015-09-11T12:33:04.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391687/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391687/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391687/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Science: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate his Department has made of the total amount that will be available to ring-fenced science and research funding organisations in each of the next five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","8265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391688","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Government protected the science ring-fence in cash terms for financial year 2015/16 at £4.6bn. In addition the Chancellor announced in December 2014 a long-term commitment to investment in science infrastructure at £1.1bn per annum in real terms to 2021.</p><p>Decisions on the amount and allocation of funding beyond 2015/16 will be made as part of the Spending Review. We cannot pre-judge the Spending Review outcome.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","8265","2015-09-11T12:33:04.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391688/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391688/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Science: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if his Department will conduct a review into the adequacy of capital investment spending as part of the science research budget allocation; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","8264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391689","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-08","<p>The effectiveness of these regulations has not recently been assessed as we have, to date, seen no evidence of this practice recurring.</p><p>However, the Information Commissioner’s Office is currently investigating some allegations of blacklisting. The Government will be paying close attention to the outcome of these investigations.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-09-08T15:53:36.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391689/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391689/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Employment Regulations Act 1999 (Blacklists) Regulations 2010","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the Employment Regulations Act 1999 (Blacklists) Regulations 2010.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","8281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391690","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring the effective and efficient management of publicly owned assets and keeps ownership of all assets under review. Where there is no longer a strong policy reason for continued public ownership or where there is potential for an asset to operate more sensibly and efficiently in the private sector, the Government will continue to look into the potential sale of public sector assets.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","8212 ; 8269 ; 8270 ; 8271 ; 8272","2015-09-11T13:18:53.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391690/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391690/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Met Office","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether any officials in his Department have worked on assessing the feasibility of privatising the Met Office.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","8350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391691","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-10","<p>The Government requires quoted companies to report on greenhouse gas emissions for which they are responsible. Quoted companies are also required to report on environmental matters to the extent it is necessary for an understanding of the company’s business within their annual report. In the Summer Budget 2015, the Government announced it will review the business energy efficiency tax landscape and consider approaches to simplify and improve the effectiveness of the regime. The review will consider the Climate Change Levy (CCL), Carbon Reduction Commitment energy efficiency scheme and their interaction with other business energy efficiency policies and regulations. The Government aims to develop a simple, fair and more efficient energy environment for business that minimises administrative burdens and incentivises business to invest, save carbon and grow. A consultation will be launched in autumn 2015. The Government also supports the Carbon Disclosure Project and encourages companies to measure their environmental risk to be better able to manage these risks strategically. The introduction of carbon reporting obligations for institutional investors in France is a matter for the French Government.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-09-10T14:22:52.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391691/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391691/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Carbon Emissions: France","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make an assessment of (a) the implications for his policies of the French government's proposed introduction of carbon reporting obligations for institutional investors under Article 48 of the Energy Transition Law and (b) the potential merits of introducing similar legislation in the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","8352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391692","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-08","<p>No licences have been granted to UAV Engines for equipment other than UAV engines or components for exports for the use of the Israeli Defence Force or other elements of Israel’s security forces since 1 January 2010.</p><p>All export licences are issued in strict accordance with the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-09-08T15:56:05.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391692/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391692/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Unmanned Air Vehicles: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of February 2015 to Question 222681, what licences have been issued since 1 January 2010 to UAV Engines Ltd for equipment other than UAV engines or components for exports for the use of the Israeli Defence Force or other elements of Israel's security forces; and on what date each such licence was issued.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Corbyn","Islington North","Jeremy Corbyn","8353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391693","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-10","<p>To be eligible for higher education funding in England, students are required to be settled in the UK, be ordinarily resident in England and have been ordinarily resident in the UK and Islands for three years prior to the first day of the first academic year of the course.</p><p> </p><p>As higher education is a devolved matter in the UK different rules may apply for students ordinarily resident in other parts of the UK.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-10T14:28:29.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391693/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391693/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Students: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, for how long UK citizens are required to reside in the UK in order to be eligible for student finance.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","8171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391694","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-10","<p>Companies House will act upon the receipt of a public complaint about a possible failure to comply with the Overseas Companies Regulations 2009 (&quot;the Regulations&quot;). It will carry out an initial investigation and then, if it considers that an offence may have been committed, it will refer the case to the Department’s solicitors to consider whether a prosecution is justified under the Code for Crown Prosecutors. The principal aim is to achieve compliance with the Regulations; therefore, prosecution action is considered a last resort.</p><p>The Department has made one prosecution under the Overseas Companies Regulations 2009. The offence related to the failure to register the opening of a UK establishment.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-09-10T14:22:18.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391694/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391694/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Overseas Companies Regulations 2009","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps Companies House is taking to enforce the Overseas Companies Regulations 2009; and how many prosecutions have been made under those Regulations to date.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","8192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391695","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-10","<p>We have received no representations on this matter. It is for providers to determine how to use their allocations and what provision and places to offer depending on learner and employer demand.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-10T14:23:32.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391695/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391695/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Arts: Foundation Courses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what representations he has received on proposed changes to the number of student places offered in art and design foundation diplomas.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","8209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391696","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-11","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I have given today to the hon. Member for Coventry South (Jim Cunningham) to PQ UIN 8264.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-11T12:33:50.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391696/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391696/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Science: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether it is his policy that the science ring-fence will remain in place.","false","Biography information for Lord Davies of Gower","Gower","Byron Davies","8211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391697","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring the effective and efficient management of publicly owned assets and keeps ownership of all assets under review. Where there is no longer a strong policy reason for continued public ownership or where there is potential for an asset to operate more sensibly and efficiently in the private sector, the Government will continue to look into the potential sale of public sector assets.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","8269 ; 8270 ; 8271 ; 8272 ; 8350","2015-09-11T13:18:52.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391697/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391697/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Ordnance Survey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether it is his policy to retain full public ownership of Ordnance Survey Limited; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","8212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391698","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Government's five point plan for tourism published on 17 July made clear our commitment to increase tourism throughout the UK's nations and regions. You can see the plan at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/446167/Tourism_-_A_Five_Point_Plan.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/446167/Tourism_-_A_Five_Point_Plan.pdf</a> Tourism is a devolved matter, but VisitBritain and VisitEngland work in partnership with VisitWales and VisitScotland, primarily through the GREAT campaign, to promote British holidays to overseas and domestic tourists.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>2014 was a record breaking year for tourism in Wales, with overnight visits to Wales by GB residents reaching 10 million, with spend of £1.7 billion. I am looking forward to having regular and constructive conversations with my Welsh counterpart.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-09-07T14:23:40.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391698/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391698/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-21","Tourism: Merthyr Tydfil and Rhymney","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to increase tourism and tourism-related jobs in Merthyr Tydfil and Rhymney.","false","Biography information for Gerald Jones","Merthyr Tydfil and Rhymney","Gerald Jones","8219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391699","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-10","<p>In March 2015 the Government launched the consultation on ‘Support for Postgraduate Study’ for Masters and Research level study. The consultation included proposals related to the terms and design features of the proposed new postgraduate Master’s loan scheme, including the eligibility of distance learning and part-time Master’s study. The responses to the consultation are currently being analysed and the Department will respond in the autumn.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-10T14:23:57.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391699/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391699/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Postgraduate Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the reasons are for the distinction, made in the Annexes to his Department's response, published in March 2015, to its consultation on Support for Post-Graduate study, between taught Masters students who are studying via distance learning and part-time taught Masters students for the purposes of the new postgraduate loans scheme proposed for England; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Iain Stewart","Milton Keynes South","Iain Stewart","8357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391700","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>As with other temporary review bodies, the Independent Commission on Freedom of Information is not subject to FOIA.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","8185","2015-09-07T12:00:12.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391700/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391700/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-21","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Written Statement of 20 June 2015, HCWS153, on Freedom of Information, whether the Freedom of Information Commission is a public authority subject to the Freedom of Information Act 2000.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","8184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391701","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>As with other temporary review bodies, the Independent Commission on Freedom of Information is not subject to FOIA.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","8184","2015-09-07T12:00:12.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391701/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391701/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-21","Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Written Statement of 20 June 2015, HCWS153, on Freedom of Information, what plans he has to issue an order under section 4 or 5 of the Freedom of Information Act 2000 in relation to the Freedom of Information Commission.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","8185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391702","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>Information on Government suppliers within a specific constituency or region is not held centrally.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-09-07T11:54:17.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391702/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391702/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-21","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many and what value of procurement contracts central Government Departments hold with suppliers in each (a) region and (b) parliamentary constituency.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","8130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391703","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-09-07T11:52:25.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391703/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391703/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-21","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many full-time equivalent staff in all Government departments and agencies in total were working on climate change adaptation in (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2012-13, (d) 2013-14 and (e) 2014-15; and if he will estimate the likely number of such staff in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","8333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391704","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-10","<p>HM Revenue and Customs received an additional £800m of funding at the Summer Budget 2015 for a range of measures to tackle evasion and non-compliance. The additional expenditure which covers both the funding and the investment is set out in line 54 of table 2.1 in Chapter 2 on page 72 of the Summer Budget 2015 document.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","8217","2015-09-10T14:58:04.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391704/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391704/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Revenue and Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2015 to Question 6496, how much of the £800 million referred to in that Answer is allocated as additional spending in the Budget.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","8292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391705","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Treasury Communications team is managed by the Chancellor’s spokesperson who is a civil servant and was therefore recruited in line with principles of Civil Service Recruitment. The Chancellor has appointed a special adviser to be his Director of Communications, who does not manage any civil servants. Special Adviser appointments are made in line with the Ministerial Code and Code of Conduct for Special Advisers.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-11T11:33:04.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391705/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391705/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Treasury: Communication","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 16 June 2015 to Question 2813, whether the Civil Service Recruitment Principles were followed in the appointment of his Department's Director of Communications.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","8296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391706","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-07","<p>The government has committed to dispose of public sector land with capacity for 150,000 homes by 2020. Meeting this goal is vital for securing the government’s high ambitions to support housing supply and affordability, while prioritising the use of brownfield land.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As part of the Spending Review process HM Treasury will be working with departments on their contributions to the overall target.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-09-07T15:09:04.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391706/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391706/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Public Sector: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 3.29 of his Department's document, A country that lives within its means: Spending Review 2015, published in July 2015, what proportion of the total amount of public sector land to be disposed he expects to be contributed by each department.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","8341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391707","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-07","<p>The information requested is not available.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-09-07T15:03:11.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391707/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391707/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Carers: Child Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of main carers of each gender in each region and constituent part of the UK who receive child tax credit.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","8248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391708","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-07","<p>As announced at Summer Budget 2015, the government will retain the current duty exemption for small cider producers until and unless a replacement scheme is established. Small cider makers are a traditional part of rural economies who help create a diverse and vibrant cider market and the government is committed to maintaining support for the industry.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK is discussing reforms to EU law with the EU Commission and other Member States, so that it explicitly allows member states to support small cider makers through the duty regime. The government is also looking at alternatives that could apply. The government will work with industry on both of these.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-09-07T15:06:36.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391708/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391708/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his policy is on duty exemption for small-scale producers; and what he took of EU directives when forming that policy.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","8255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391709","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-10","<p>HM Treasury has previously considered the economic analysis provided by the tourism sector on the impact a VAT cut would have on economic growth and jobs. The conclusion the Government reached is that a VAT cut for the sector would not produce sufficient economic growth to outweigh the revenue shortfall.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-10T14:59:29.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391709/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391709/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Tourism: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate the potential number of jobs that would be created by a reduction in VAT for the tourism industry.","false","Biography information for Gerald Jones","Merthyr Tydfil and Rhymney","Gerald Jones","8199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391710","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-07","<p>Companies House’s principal roles are to incorporate and dissolve limited companies, register the information companies are legally required to supply, and make that information available to the public. There are no plans to change these functions.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-09-07T08:45:35.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391710/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391710/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Companies House","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what his policy is on the future of Companies House; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","8235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391711","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring the effective and efficient management of publicly owned assets and keeping ownership of all assets under review. Where there is no longer a strong policy reason for continued public ownership or where there is potential for an asset to operate more sensibly and efficiently in the private sector, the Government will continue to look into the potential sale of public sector assets.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The net asset value of the government’s holdings for bodies in which it holds a stake is estimated in the annual report of the parent department or within the accounts of the organisation (depending on the precise ownership and structure).</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","8237 ; 8238","2015-09-07T14:52:49.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391711/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391711/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Royal Mint","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether officials in his Department has worked on assessing the feasibility of privatising the Royal Mint.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","8236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391712","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring the effective and efficient management of publicly owned assets and keeping ownership of all assets under review. Where there is no longer a strong policy reason for continued public ownership or where there is potential for an asset to operate more sensibly and efficiently in the private sector, the Government will continue to look into the potential sale of public sector assets.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The net asset value of the government’s holdings for bodies in which it holds a stake is estimated in the annual report of the parent department or within the accounts of the organisation (depending on the precise ownership and structure).</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","8236 ; 8238","2015-09-07T14:52:50.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391712/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391712/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Royal Mint","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether it is his policy to retain full public ownership of the Royal Mint; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","8237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391713","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring the effective and efficient management of publicly owned assets and keeping ownership of all assets under review. Where there is no longer a strong policy reason for continued public ownership or where there is potential for an asset to operate more sensibly and efficiently in the private sector, the Government will continue to look into the potential sale of public sector assets.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The net asset value of the government’s holdings for bodies in which it holds a stake is estimated in the annual report of the parent department or within the accounts of the organisation (depending on the precise ownership and structure).</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","8236 ; 8237","2015-09-07T14:52:49.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391713/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391713/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Public Bodies","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate his Department has made of the value of the (a) Royal Mint, (b) Land Registry, (c) Ordnance Survey, (d) Met Office and (e) National Air Traffic Services.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","8238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391714","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-11","<p>The independent Senior Salaries Review Body (SSRB), which reports to Cabinet Office Ministers, recommends the pay framework for the Senior Civil Servants within government and the Prime Minister responds via ministerial statement the government’s response. HM Treasury applied pay increases in line with agreed framework within the resources available for the Senior Civil Servants. These increases were signed off by the HMT Executive management Board.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-11T10:41:21.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391714/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391714/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Treasury: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which Minister in his Department authorised the pay rises for his Department's senior executives in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","8274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391715","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-16","<p>The new National Living Wage (NLW) is an essential part of moving to a higher wage, lower tax, lower welfare society; it ensures that work pays, and reduces reliance on the State topping up wages through the benefits system.</p><p> </p><p>For younger workers, the priority is to secure work and gain experience - something that is already reflected in the National Minimum Wage (NMW) rate structure where the youth rate is currently £1.40 lower than the adult rate.</p><p> </p><p>Just as the Low Pay Commission will recommend the pace of increase for the NLW, they will continue to recommend the NMW rates for all workers under 25 at a level that maximises their earnings without damaging employment prospects by setting it too high.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-09-16T10:19:14.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391715/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391715/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Living Wage: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, for what reasons the new Living Wage does not apply to those under 25.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","8275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391716","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-10","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</a></p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-10T14:55:11.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391716/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391716/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Farms: Tenants","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will meet the Tenant Farmers' Association to discuss its proposals for taxation of agricultural land to encourage longer term farm business tenancies.","false","Biography information for Neil Parish","Tiverton and Honiton","Neil Parish","8278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391717","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-11","<p>Over the last Parliament the number of people in employment increased by almost 2 million, meaning on average an extra 1,000 people in work every single day. The number working full-time increased by 1.5 million making up 76 per cent of the rise in employment, while the number of part-time workers rose by 482,000.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-11T11:39:04.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391717/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391717/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Part-time Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to paragraph 2.11 of the Spending Review 2015 (Cm 9112), how many of the two million jobs referred to in that paragraph are part-time.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","8289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391718","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-07","<p>The table below shows the UK contributions to the World Bank (specifically to IBRD, the non-concessional lending arm of the World Bank) in paid in capital and callable capital in each of the last five years.</p><p> </p><p>Please note that the UK did not pay in additional capital to IBRD or contribute additional callable capital in 2010. Additional contributions to multilateral development bank’s capital are infrequent and only happen through General or Selective Capital Increases (known as GCIs and SCIs). The most recent of these for IBRD became effective in 2011.</p><p> </p><p>The paid in amount is fixed in US dollar terms. As such the Sterling amount varies slightly each year depending on the exchange rate. The callable element increases on a pro-rata basis as each paid in contribution is made and is reported in US Dollars in IBRD’s accounts.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong>Paid- in capital - Sterling paid equivalent </strong><strong>to US $31,114,059</strong></p><p><strong> (paid in December of each stated year)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Callable capital (as stated in IBRD audited </strong><strong>accounts at June 30th of following year)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p>n/a</p></td><td><p>$7,832.2m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><br> £19,957,703</p></td><td><p>$8,319.6m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p>£19,451,149</p></td><td><p>$8,807.1m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p>£19,047,480</p></td><td><p>$9,294.4m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>£19,915,547</p></td><td><p>$9,781.9m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-07T14:57:52.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391718/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391718/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-21","World Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the UK contribution was to the World Bank in (a) paid in capital and (b) callable capital in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","8134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391719","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-07","<p>The National Living Wage supports the UK in moving from a low wage, high tax, high welfare society to a higher wage, lower tax, lower welfare society.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We are working with employers in the social care sector, including care providers from the voluntary sector, to understand how the introduction of the National Living Wage will affect them.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-09-07T13:13:46.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391719/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391719/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Care Homes: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of the introduction of the National Living Wage on charitable residential care homes who do not benefit from the reduction in corporation tax rates.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","8140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391720","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Deposit Guarantee Scheme Directive (DGSD) is a single market measure to ensure that depositors are entitled to the same level of protection wherever they deposit their money, and that UK firms are not competitively disadvantaged in relation to firms in other EEA jurisdictions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As a result of the current strength of the pound in relation to the euro, it has been necessary for the Prudential Regulation Authority to review the sterling coverage limit. However, the Government has taken action to ensure that UK depositors are not exposed to a sudden reduction in the level of protection they receive.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury has laid a statutory instrument to ensure that depositors who are currently entitled to £85,000 of protection from the Financial Services Compensation Scheme will continue to be until 31 December 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This will ensure that there is sufficient time available for depositors to be made aware of the changes, and to take such steps as they feel necessary to manage their financial affairs appropriately in light of this change. More than 95% of UK retail depositors are expected to remain unaffected by the change to the coverage limit.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-07T09:09:07.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391720/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391720/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Financial Services Compensation Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for what reasons he proposes to reduce the upper limit of compensation payments for the Financial Services Compensation Scheme.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","8142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391721","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Chancellor has not introduced any financial measures which are specifically targeted towards residential care homes for elderly people run by charities. However a range of measures have been introduced by the Government to support the social care sector and charities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Central Government provides funding to local authorities to purchase care for the needs of their population from local providers. In addition to this funding, important steps have been taken to improve the care and support landscape within which residential care homes operate. The first phase of the care and support reforms enshrined in the Care Act 2014 came into force in April this year, introducing the biggest reforms to care and support in over 65 years. For the first time ever, we have a single, modern legal framework for care and support that places the person and their health and wellbeing at its heart. There are now national minimum eligibility criteria for care and support across England. Carers now have the right to support to meet their needs, and deferred payment agreements are available across England ensuring that people should not be forced to sell their home in order to pay for their care in their lifetime.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The government recognises the vital role of charities and their important position in local communities. This is why, for example, the government also provides support for charities through tax reliefs, of which Gift Aid makes up over £1 billion. Total tax reliefs to charities and their donors were worth over £4.5 billion last year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-07T15:14:00.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391721/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391721/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Care Homes: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what financial measures he has introduced to help residential care homes for elderly people run by charities since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","8143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391722","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-07","<p>There are no specific corporation tax exemptions for residential care homes for elderly people. However, residential care homes may claim an exemption from corporation tax when they are recognised as a charity for tax purposes by HM Revenue and Customs.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-07T15:15:02.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391722/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391722/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Care Homes: Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many residential care homes for elderly people are exempt from corporation tax.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","8144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391723","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-07","<p>HM Treasury officials routinely engage with the Office of Budget Responsibility on a range of issues. It is for the independent Office for National Statistics to determine the classification of economic activity for National Accounts purposes.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-09-07T15:07:29.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391723/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391723/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Social Rented Housing: Landlords","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Summer Budget 2015, what advice his Department received from the Office of Budget Responsibility on the fiscal effect of policy changes to the classification of Registered Social Landlords.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","8193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391724","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-07","<p>The financial penalty imposed on the Information Commissioner’s Office will be retained in the UK Consolidated Fund. This is the central account which receives government revenues and ensures that the government can distribute the funds appropriately to support its priorities.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-09-07T15:10:01.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391724/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391724/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Information Commissioner: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on what the fines imposed on the Information Commissioner's Office for excessive pay rises will be spent.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","8190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391725","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-11","<p>The deadline for responses to the business rates review was 12 June 2015. We have been undertaking analysis and considering the wide variety of views put forward in stakeholder responses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Summer Budget confirmed that the review will be fiscally neutral and will conclude by the end of the year.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-11T10:38:49.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391725/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391725/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress his Department has made on its review of  business rates; and what the projected timetable is for that review.","false","Biography information for Mr Marcus Fysh","Yeovil","Marcus Fysh","8204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391726","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-10","<p>HM Revenue and Customs received an additional £800m of funding at the Summer Budget 2015 for a range of measures to tackle evasion and non-compliance. The additional expenditure which covers both the funding and the investment is set out in line 54 of table 2.1 in Chapter 2 on page 72 of the Summer Budget 2015 document.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","8292","2015-09-10T14:58:04.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391726/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391726/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Revenue and Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2015 to Question 6496, how much of the £800 million referred to in the Answer will be invested in each year of the present Parliament.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","8217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391727","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-08","<p>Monitoring the market for misselling is the responsibility of the regulators, the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) and the Pensions Regulator. The FCA, in line with its remit to protect consumers and ensure markets function in consumers’ interests, has specifically committed to monitoring developments in the retirement income market closely and to take action where consumers are coming to harm or where the market is not operating competitively.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Alongside this the Treasury has launched a consultation looking at options to address excessive charges for early exit penalties, and making the process for transferring pensions from one scheme to another quicker and smoother.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government remains in close contact with the regulators, and other organisations such as industry trade bodies, on these issues.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-08T15:01:07.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391727/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391727/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Pensions: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the likely trends in the mis-selling of pension products in Scotland arising from the introduction of new pension flexibilities on 6 April 2015.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","8173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391728","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-11","<p>Removing the Climate Change Levy (CCL) renewables exemption will have no direct impact on the UK’s ability to meet its climate change and renewables targets.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This Government takes its environmental responsibilities very seriously and is committed to meeting its climate change commitments as cost effectively as possible. We are currently making good progress on this, with emissions down 30% since 1990.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>One third of the value of the CCL renewables exemption was going to support renewable generation projects based overseas. These projects do not contribute to our climate change commitments and so provided poor value for money for UK taxpayers.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-09-11T10:28:16.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391728/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391728/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Climate Change Levy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he made in advance of the Summer Budget 2015 of the effect on the UK's carbon footprint of applying the climate change levy to renewable electricity.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","8150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391729","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-08","<p /> <p>The information requested is not available.</p><p> </p><p>To prevent young people slipping straight into a life on benefits, from April 2017 the Government will remove the automatic entitlement to housing support for new claims in Universal Credit from 18-21 year olds who are out of work. This will ensure young people in the benefits system face the same choices as young people who work and who may not be able to afford to leave home.</p><p> </p><p>We will ensure that vulnerable young people who are in need of support for their housing needs continue to receive it. Government will consider the impact in line with our legal obligations as part of that process.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-09-08T16:00:55.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391729/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391729/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-21","Housing Benefit: Copeland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of 18 to 21 year olds in Copeland constituency that will no longer be entitled to housing benefit following measures announced in the Summer Budget 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","8176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391730","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-11","<p>Updated Information on the impacts of Tax-Free Childcare on the labour and childcare markets will be published in due course.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","7920","2015-09-11T10:29:14.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391730/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391730/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has made an assessment of any potential link between the introduction of tax-free childcare and the (a) cost and (b) demand for childcare by providers.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","8179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391731","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-07","<p>The European Financial Stabilisation Mechanism (EFSM) loan to Greece, agreed on 17 July, includes legally binding arrangements to ensure that the UK would incur no costs in the case of a default by Greece. In advance of disbursement, a legally binding agreement (a “Settlement and Payment Agreement”) was signed, which grants the UK and all non-euro area Member States immediate access to collateral, equivalent to their full potential liability, in the event that Greece fails to repay the EFSM loan. The €1.96 billion of collateral is in a ring-fenced account at the European Central Bank.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Subsequently, the Government secured an amendment to the EFSM regulation to ensure that similar legally binding full guarantee arrangements will be in place for any future use of the EFSM for the purpose of securing the financial stability of a member of the single currency.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-07T15:31:04.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391731/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391731/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","European Financial Stabilisation Mechanism","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what legal rights the UK has to reclaim potential losses brought about by the use of the European Financial Stabilisation Mechanism to bail out Eurozone states.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","8305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391732","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-07","<p>UK Government Investments will be established in the autumn, with an intention to complete any transfer activity for the start of the next financial year.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-07T15:29:44.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391732/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391732/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","UK Financial Investments: Shareholder Executive","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the statement in his speech to the Confederation of British Industry on 20 May 2015 that the Government plans to merge UK Financial Investments and the Shareholder Executive into one organisation; what his proposed timetable is for that merger.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","8318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391733","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-11","<p>The National Policy Statement (NPS) for Ports (<a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-policy-statement-for-ports" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-policy-statement-for-ports</a>), designated in 2012, includes guidance about onshore electricity supply at paragraphs 5.7.12ff. Although the NPS primarily addresses nationally significant infrastructure projects as defined under the Planning Act 2008, for which it has legal force, it also stands as potentially relevant guidance for the Marine Management Organisation and for local authorities when dealing with smaller ports projects.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-09-11T09:06:39.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391733/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391733/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","Ports: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will provide guidance to local authorities considering planning applications for cruise terminals on the comparative merits of berthed cruise ships receiving energy supplies from onshore sources and generating their own energy from diesel fuel.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","8223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391734","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-07","<p>This information is not held by my Department or the Department of Health which leads on public health issues.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-09-07T10:08:41.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391734/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391734/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-21","Public Health Funerals: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many Public Health Funerals have been conducted in (a) Copeland constituency and (b) Cumbria in each of the last 20 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","8227"
