he Government extended a right request flexible working arrangements after a 26 weeks’ qualifying period, building on a previous entitlement for some carers. This will help to normalise the kind of flexible working patterns that can help carers balance different responsibilities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>On 13 February the Government launched a joint Department of Health, Government Equality Office and Department for Work and Pensions investment of £1.6 million in pilots in nine local authority areas to explore ways in which people can be supported to combine work and care. Through the scheme, nine pilot areas will explore how professional support, technology, volunteering, informal networks and support from employers can be combined to ease the pressure of caring. This will build on the requirement in the Care Act to consider support for employment as part of an assessment of eligible needs, set out above.</p><p> </p><p>More broadly, the Department for Work and Pensions continues to invest in supporting carers to return to work. For example, income replacement benefits help people and households on lower incomes, and include a carer premium, currently £34.60 a week. An equivalent additional amount applies in Pension Credit. Universal Credit will also include a carer element at the rate of £150.39 per monthly assessment period. This means that lower-income carers can be better off than others who receive these benefits.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>On 1 July my Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State (Mr Jeremy Hunt) announced that I will develop a new carers’ strategy that looks at the best of international practice and examines what more we can do to support existing carers and the new carers we will need.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","8158 ; 8159 ; 8191","2015-09-08T14:54:06.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391845/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391845/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-21","Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans his Department has to ensure that healthcare professionals identify (a) people caring for people living with and beyond cancer and (b) other carers and signpost them to available services and support.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","8160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391846","Department of Health","false","2015-09-07","<p>There were 3,752 finished admission episodes for the Lancashire Care NHS Foundation Trust in the year 2013-14¹.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information on activity sub-contracted from one facility to another is not collected centrally. We have written to Derek Brown, Chair of the Lancashire Care NHS Foundation Trust informing him of the hon. Member’s enquiry. He will reply shortly and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Library.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>¹<em>Source</em>: The Health and Social Care Information Centre</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>Notes: </em></p><p> </p><ol><li>Activity includes English NHS hospitals and English NHS commissioned activity in the independent sector.</li><li>2. A finished admission episode (FAE) is the first period of admitted patient care under one consultant within one healthcare provider. FAEs are counted against the year or month in which the admission episode finishes. Admissions do not represent the number of patients, as a person may have more than one admission within the period.</li></ol><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-09-07T12:48:20.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391846/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391846/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-21","Lancashire Care NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many patients were admitted by Lancashire Care hospitals in 2014; and how many of those admissions were to (a) NHS facilities, (b) privately-run facilities in Lancashire, (c) named NHS facilities and (d) named private facilities outside Lancashire.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","8139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391847","Department of Health","false","2015-09-07","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Government recently published statutory guidance setting out how local authorities should meet new duties in the Care Act around promoting a sustainable care market in their area. This includes consideration of the actual costs of care and support when negotiating fee levels with providers in the locality.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-09-07T12:42:19.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391847/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391847/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-21","Care Homes: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of elderly residents of residential care homes run by charities who receive subsidised care from the operating charity.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","8141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391848","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>Since 2004, the Department has awarded 107 contracts to the University of York, of which 105 are entirely research based. The total value of all contracts is £92.96 million. Information prior to 2004 is not held.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Since 2007 the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has awarded 10 contracts to the University of York (this figure includes six contracts awarded to York Health Economics Consortium, which is based at the University). The total value of these contracts is £1.16 million. NICE does not hold information relating to contracts awarded prior to 2007.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-09-11T10:54:20.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391848/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391848/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-21","York University","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many contracts have been awarded to the University of York by (a) his Department and (b) NICE since 1999; and how much funding has been allocated through each such contract by (i) his Department and (ii) NICE since 1999.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Steve Baker","8145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391849","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>We are advised by Monitor that King’s College Hospital NHS Foundation Trust has developed a referral to treatment (RTT) Recovery Plan that focuses on backlog clearance and validation in order to secure a return to compliance against RTT standards, and a validated waiting list underpinned by robust RTT policies, procedures and systems.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Trust agreed with commissioners to temporarily suspend reporting whilst this Recovery Plan was implemented and as a result no national reporting against national RTT standards has taken place year to date for 2015/16. The Trust continues to provide commissioners with a weekly snapshot of unvalidated activity and monthly progress reports during this reporting suspension period.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It is expected that the Trust will resume reporting in in November 2015 as agreed with Monitor, NHS England and local commissioners.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-09-11T13:46:26.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391849/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391849/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-21","King's College Hospital NHS Foundation Trust: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the reasons are for the delay in publishing the May 2015 referral to treatment waiting time data for King's College Hospital NHS Foundation Trust; and what action he plans to take to ensure that such data is published as soon as possible.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","8129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391850","Home Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>In 2014 Her Majesty’s Passport Office was notified of 299,531 lost, stolen or “other” passports. The category &quot;other&quot; is used by Her Majesty’s Passport Office predominantly when a passport is declared damaged or destroyed. In 241,389 instances, the lost, stolen or other report was accompanied by an application for a replacement passport. A total of 58,142 applicants did not apply for passports immediately at the time of the reported loss. It is not possible to provide a figure for the number of people that applied for a replacement passport after notifying Her Majesty’s Passport Office about the loss of or damage to their passport.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Report Type</p></td><td><p>Replacement Passport Applications at time of notification</p></td><td><p>Notification of loss but no replacement requested</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lost</p></td><td><p>235,883</p></td><td><p>42,186</p></td><td><p>278,069</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Stolen</p></td><td><p>4,096</p></td><td><p>14,715</p></td><td><p>18, 811</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>1,410</p></td><td><p>1,241</p></td><td><p>2,651</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>241,389</p></td><td><p>58,142</p></td><td><p>299,531</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-07T15:34:20.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391850/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391850/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-21","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people reported (a) lost and (b) stolen passports to the Passport Office in 2014; and how many of those people were issued with a replacement.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","8136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391851","Home Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>Resourcing is an operational matter for chief officers. We have prioritised child sexual abuse as a national threat which will help to ensure that police forces and Police and Crime Commissioners have in place the capabilities they need to protect children from sexual abuse.</p><p>In 2015/16 the Home Office provided an additional £10 million to the National Crime Agency for the creation of more specialist teams to tackle online child sexual exploitation. We have also made available £1.7 million to fund Operation Hydrant, which coordinates the handling of multiple non-recent child sexual abuse investigations specifically concerning institutions or persons of public prominence, and £1.5 million to support regional coordinators and analysts to oversee the implementation of the National Policing Plan for tackling Child Sexual Exploitation.</p><p>Additionally, the Home Office and Ministry of Justice announced an additional £7 million for victims services supporting survivors of sexual violence in 2014/15 and 2015/16.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-09-07T15:28:09.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391851/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391851/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-21","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what amount of resource has been available to the police to (a) protect children from sexual abuse, (b) carry out investigations in relation to (i) current and (ii) historic child sexual abuse cases in each of the last five years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","8220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391852","Home Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>This information is not held centrally by the Home Office and may be held by the force itself.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-07T15:51:53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391852/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391852/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-21","Racial Harassment: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much was paid out in compensation (a) in total and (b) per case to victims of racial abuse by police officers in London in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","8224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391853","Home Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>Protestors’ rights need to be balanced with the rights of others to go about their business without fear of intimidation or serious disruption to the community.</p><p>As set out in the Public Order Act 1986, the police have a range of powers to manage the impact of demonstrations, including the ability to impose conditions on assemblies and public processions to prevent serious public disorder, serious damage to property, or serious disruption to the life of the community.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-07T15:13:07.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391853/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391853/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-21","Community Relations: Dudley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will meet the hon. Member for Dudley South and a delegation of civic, faith and business leaders from Dudley to discuss the effect that demonstrations by far-right organisations are having on community life and trade in that town.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","8203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391854","Home Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>Since 2005 the proportion of applications that have been granted Indefinite Leave to Remain who have previously had Discretionary Leave status broken down by age group is as follows: Age 0 to 6 - 520 Age 7 to 18 – 3,160 Age 19 to 30 – 15,300 Age 31 to 40 – 16,340 Age 41 to 50 – 8,640 Age 51 to 60 – 2,815 Age 61 and over – 1,865</p><p>The Home Office does not hold data to show the proportion of applications that have Indefinite Leave to Remain who have also had Discretionary Leave status, based on their educational qualifications.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-07T16:26:20.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391854/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391854/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-21","Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of applications for permanent leave to remain from people who have had discretionary leave to remain status (a) in each age group and (b) with each level of educational qualification for at least 10 years.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","8258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391855","Home Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>For national security reasons we do not disclose the detailed allocation of police counter-terrorism capabilities or resource.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-09-07T15:35:59.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391855/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391855/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-21","Counter-terrorism: Turkey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many UK counter-terrorism police staff are based in Turkey.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","8311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391857","Home Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>We are unable to provide the information requested as to produce an accurate number would require a manual review of records matched between different Home Office data systems, which would only be achievable at a disproportionate cost.</p><p>The UK has a proud tradition of providing protection to those who need it most. Between 2011 and March this year, we granted asylum or other forms of leave to over 4,200 Syrian nationals and dependants.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-07T15:44:42.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391857/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391857/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-21","Asylum: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Syrian refugees granted asylum in the UK were studying in the UK at the time their asylum application was made in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","8239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391858","Home Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Home Office is able to provide some of the information requested, but is unable to provide information on which applications are from members of the same family, as to obtain this would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p>The numbers of family reunion visas issued &amp; refused in total and broken down by age group, gender and the specific nationalities requested is set out in the table below.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-07T15:34:23.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391858/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391858/answer","8377 annex 23.07.15[1] v2.docx","8377 annex 23.07.15[1] v2.docx","Numer of family reunion visa issued & refused","Numer of family reunion visa issued & refused","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391858/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-21","Entry Clearances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications for Refugee Family Reunion (under Part 11 Immigration Rules) have resulted in the granting of entry clearance to children under 18 and the refusal of entry clearance to female children over 18 from the same family (a) in total and (b) for families originating from (i) Syria, (ii) Afghanistan and (iii) Iran in the last two years for which records exist.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Corbyn","Islington North","Jeremy Corbyn","8377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391859","Home Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>Her Majesty's Government closed Tier 1 (Post-Study Work) in April 2012 and has no plans to reintroduce the route for any international graduates, including those who have studied at Scottish universities.</p><p>We closed the Tier 1 (Post Study Work) route because too many individuals in the route were unemployed or in low-skilled work, and too many were using the student route merely as a means to work in the UK, without any intention of study, which does not help hard-working people or our educational institutions.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-07T15:37:28.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391859/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391859/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-21","Overseas Students: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has any plans to reintroduce tier 1 post-study work visas for students completing their studies at Scottish universities.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","8346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391860","Home Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>Her Majesty's Government has no plans to open Tier 3 of the Points Based System.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-07T15:46:19.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391860/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391860/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-21","Migrant Workers: Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has any plans to open the tier 3 category of visas to new applicants.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","8345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391861","Home Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>Figures on how many UK nationals have crossed into Syria from the Turkish border and returned to the UK in the last 12 months are not available.</p><p>However, we are aware of around 700 people from the UK who are of concern to the Police and Security Services and who are thought to have travelled to the region since the start of the conflict. We estimate that around half of those have returned.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-07T15:42:21.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391861/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391861/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-21","British Nationals Abroad: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate her Department has made of the number of UK nationals who have crossed into Syria from the Turkish border and have since returned to the UK in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","8312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391862","Home Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Home Secretary and Home Office officials frequently meet with international partners, including Turkey, to discuss issues related to counter-terrorism. Turkey is a key partner in the fight against terrorism and we work closely with them to prevent UK nationals travelling to Syria for the purposes of terrorism. Discussions with Turkish counterparts have focused on cooperation on border security, law enforcement and stopping the travel of British nationals into Syria.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-09-07T15:45:42.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391862/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391862/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-21","British Nationals Abroad: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent representations she has made to her Turkish counterpart on developing a joint strategy to prevent UK nationals crossing over the border with Turkey into Syria.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","8313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391863","Home Office","false","2015-09-07","<p>My officials are in regular discussions with the Surveillance Camera Commissioner and his team, and those discussions cover a range of issues in relation to the regulation of overt CCTV and other surveillance camera systems in public places. We are aware that he has recently written to all local authorities reminding them of their obligations under the code and requested that they complete and publish the self-assessment tool, that covers all the principles.</p><p>The Commissioner will be presenting his Annual Report to the Home Secretary in the near future, and I anticipate that this will include commentary on the surveillance camera use by local authorities and other relevant authorities under S33(5) of the Protection of Freedoms Act 2012. That report is intended to provide the Government, Parliament and the public an opportunity to reflect on the regulation of surveillance.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-07T16:19:15.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391863/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391863/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-21","CCTV: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions (a) she, (b) other Ministers in her Department and (c) officials in her Department have had with the Surveillance Camera Commissioner about compliance to Principle 1 of the Surveillance Camera Code of Practice 2013 by local authorities in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","8297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391864","House of Commons Commission","false","2015-09-07","<p>An option to move Parliament out of the Palace of Westminster to a new purpose-built building was included in the Restoration and Renewal Pre-Feasibility Study of 2012. The House of Commons Commission reviewed that study on 29 October 2012. It decided to rule out the option of constructing a new building away from Westminster and agreed that no further analysis would be undertaken on this option. The House Committee of the House of Lords took a similar view.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2015-09-07T14:10:32.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391864/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391864/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2015-07-21","Palace of Westminster","1","House of Commons","To ask the Rt. Hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, whether options other than remaining in the Palace of Westminster have been considered for the long-term future of the House.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","8344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391865","House of Commons Commission","false","2015-09-07","<p>The two Houses have established a Joint Committee on the Palace of Westminster which will report and make recommendations to both Houses on the future restoration and renewal of the Palace. It will be for the two Houses to decide in due course whether or not they wish to make changes to the layout and seating arrangements of their respective Chambers in conjunction with the essential replacement of service infrastructure and other repairs to the fabric of the building. I am sure that the Joint Committee will be happy to receive the hon. Lady's ideas on this subject.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2015-09-07T14:11:20.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391865/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391865/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2015-07-21","House of Commons Chamber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Rt. Hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, whether consideration has been given to ensuring that there will be adequate provision for every hon. Member to attend proceedings and take part in proceedings in the Chamber following the restoration and renewal of the Palace of Westminster.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","8348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391866","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-07","<p>DFID funding focused on biodiversity was £29.1 million in 2010-11, £20.6 million in 2011-12, £18.3 million in 2012-13 and £35.1 million in 2013-14. This includes our relevant contributions to the Global Environment Facility. Data for 2014/15 and 2015/16 will be published once available.</p><p> </p><p>DFID has also transferred £5.5 million per annum since 2011 to DEFRA for the Darwin Initiative. This is not accounted for in the above numbers.</p><p> </p><p>Future funding levels for biodiversity will be determined as part of the current Spending Review process</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","8338","2015-09-07T15:05:21.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391866/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391866/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-21","Developing Countries: Biodiversity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the total value was of projects funded by her Department to improve or conserve biodiversity in (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2012-13, (d) 2013-14 and (e) 2014-15; and what such spending is expected to be in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","8337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391867","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-07","<p>DFID funding focused on biodiversity was £29.1 million in 2010-11, £20.6 million in 2011-12, £18.3 million in 2012-13 and £35.1 million in 2013-14. This includes our relevant contributions to the Global Environment Facility. Data for 2014/15 and 2015/16 will be published once available.</p><p> </p><p>DFID has also transferred £5.5 million per annum since 2011 to DEFRA for the Darwin Initiative. This is not accounted for in the above numbers.</p><p> </p><p>Future funding levels for biodiversity will be determined as part of the current Spending Review process</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","8337","2015-09-07T15:05:21.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391867/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391867/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-21","Developing Countries: Biodiversity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what her Department's total spending on projects to improve or conserve biodiversity was in (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2012-13, (d) 2013-14 and (e) 2014-15; and what such spending is expected to be in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","8338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391868","Department for International Development","true","2015-09-07","<p>DFID support to help people adapt to the impacts of climate is delivered in an integrated way through a range of programmes. Since the International Climate Fund was established in 2011/12 approximate funding is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>2011/12 - £136m</p><p>2012/13 – £212m</p><p>2013/14 –<ins class="ministerial"> £228m</ins> <del class="ministerial">£304m </del></p><p> </p><p>Data for 2014/15 and 2015/16 will be published once available.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Future funding levels for spend on climate change will be determined as part of the current Spending Review process.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-07T15:03:45.53Z","2015-09-09T17:24:55.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391868/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391868/answer","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391868/answer/previousversion/19786","Biography information for Grant Shapps","20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-21","Developing Countries: Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what her Department's total spending was on climate change adaptation in (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2012-13, (d) 2013-14 and (e) 2014-15; and what that spending is expected to be in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","8336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391869","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Department for International Development does not provide any financial support to the Government of Iraq, in loans, through the international development budget, or through other international bodies to support reconstruction of areas recaptured from ISIL.</p><p> </p><p>Since summer 2014, DFID has committed £59.5 million to help address the needs of the 8.6 million people across Iraq that require some form of humanitarian assistance. This funding is delivered via UN agencies and humanitarian organisations.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-09-07T15:02:09.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391869/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391869/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-21","Iraq: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether the Government is providing any financial support to the Iraqi Government (a) in loans, (b) through the international development budget and (c) through other international bodies to support reconstruction of areas recaptured from ISIL.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","8246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391870","Department for International Development","true","2015-09-07","<p>DFID support to help people adapt to the impacts of climate is delivered in an integrated way through a range of programmes. Since the International Climate Fund was established in 2011/12 approximate funding is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>2011/12 - £136m</p><p>2012/13 – £212m</p><p>2013/14 –<ins class="ministerial"> £228m</ins> <del class="ministerial">£304m</del></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Data for 2014/15 and 2015/16 will be published once available.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Future funding levels for spend on climate change will be determined as part of the current Spending Review process.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-07T15:03:45.437Z","2015-09-09T17:25:19.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391870/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391870/answer","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391870/answer/previousversion/19758","Biography information for Grant Shapps","20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-21","Developing Countries: Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the total value was of projects funded by her Department on climate change adaptation in each year since 2010-11; and how much is planned to be spent in each year up to 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","8284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391871","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-07","<p>According to Save the Children, the level of acute and chronic malnutrition in the camps is poor. The most recent reports state that acute malnutrition was between 8.5% and 11.8% in the different camp areas, and stunting up to 52%.</p><p> </p><p>DFID is providing funding for treatment of severe acute and chronic malnutrition, as well as funding for water and sanitation work that helps to prevent malnutrition. Over 126,000 internally displaced and conflict affected people in Rakhine benefit from our support to water and sanitation and nutrition.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>DFID is one of the largest bilateral humanitarian donors in Rakhine, and has provided over £18 million since 2012.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-09-07T15:01:00.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391871/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391871/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-21","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what reports she has received on the levels of malnutrition in camps for internally displaced Rohingya in Rakhine State, Burma; and what aid the UK Government is providing to those camps.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","8213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391872","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-07","<p>The UK pledged £20 million in early recovery assistance at the Gaza reconstruction conference in Cairo last year. We have disbursed all of this pledge and will disburse further funds for Gaza throughout the financial year.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-09-07T14:58:42.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391872/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391872/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-21","Palestinians: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much of the £32 million of aid pledged by the UK at the Cairo Donor Conference in 2014 to cover disposal of unexploded ordnance, rubble clearing and reconstructive surgery has been disbursed to date; and how much more such aid is planned to be sent in future.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","8210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391873","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-09","<p /> <p>It is an offence under section 168 of the Equalities Act 2010 to refuse to take an assistance dog in a taxi or private hire vehicle. The maximum penalty is a level 3 fine (up to £1,000)</p><p>Sentencing guidelines are a matter for the independent Sentencing Council. Guidelines are available on their website. Guidelines are not available for all offences, but there are general guidelines covering the assessment of seriousness, and magistrates’ guidelines about what to consider when determining the fine in individual cases, taking account of the seriousness of the offence and the means of the offender.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-09-09T14:46:59.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391873/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391873/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-21","Taxis: Guide Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will introduce sentencing guidelines to stop taxis and private hire vehicles from refusing to carry guide dogs.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","8187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391874","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-17","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-09-17T16:52:19.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391874/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391874/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-21","Courts: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much was spent each month on the (a) maintenance and (b) running costs of court buildings that have been closed in the period up to their disposal since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","8165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391875","Ministry of Justice","true","2015-09-14","<p>There are seven types of applications that can be made to the First-tier Tribunal (Property Chamber - Residential Property). <ins class="ministerial">Two types of applications, namely leasehold disputes and leasehold enfranchisement, are types that</ins><del class="ministerial">Leasehold dispute applications and leasehold enfranchisement applications</del> relate to leasehold matters; the remaining five application types do not usually have any connection to leaseholds.</p><br /><p>Data specific to such cases relating to leasehold are not routinely published. The table below <ins class="ministerial">contains statistics sourced using internal data and </ins>sets out the number of applications made to the Property Chamber for cases relating to leasehold in each of the last five years.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Number of Leasehold Applications</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Number of Leasehold Enfranchisement Applications</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2010/11</ins><del class="ministerial">2009/10</del></p></td><td><p>3216</p></td><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2010/11</ins><del class="ministerial">2009/10</del></p></td><td><p>3118</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2011/12</ins><del class="ministerial">2010/11</del></p></td><td><p>3122</p></td><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2011/12</ins><del class="ministerial">2010/11</del></p></td><td><p>3284</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2012/13</ins><del class="ministerial">2011/12</del></p></td><td><p>3645</p></td><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2012/13</ins><del class="ministerial">2011/12</del></p></td><td><p>3574</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2013/14</ins><del class="ministerial">2012/13</del></p></td><td><p>3299</p></td><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2013/14</ins><del class="ministerial">2012/13</del></p></td><td><p>3857</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2014/15</ins><del class="ministerial">2013/14</del></p></td><td><p>2773</p></td><td><p><ins class="ministerial">2014/15</ins><del class="ministerial">2013/14</del></p></td><td><p>5069</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>Leasehold applications relate to Service Charges, Breach of Covenants, Administration Charges and Appointment of Managers. Leasehold Enfranchisement applications relate to the buying of a property’s freehold and extending a lease.</p><br /><p>As this data is drawn from internal data it has not undergone the usual quality assurance work associated with statistical publications.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-09-14T09:39:27.473Z","2015-11-05T15:10:37.99Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391875/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391875/answer","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391875/answer/previousversion/20819","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-21","First-tier Tribunal: Leasehold","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many of each type of application listed on the HM Tribunals Service website were made to the Residential Property (First Tier) Tribunal for cases relating to leasehold in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","8294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391876","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-08","<p>This information is published as part of the Offender Management Statistics Quarterly publication, and is available in Table 1.9 at the link below.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/449240/prison-population-apr-jun-2015.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/449240/prison-population-apr-jun-2015.xlsx</a></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-09-08T13:45:14.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391876/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391876/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-21","Prison Sentences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people in England and Wales are serving imprisonment for public protection sentences.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","8287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391877","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-09","<p /> <p>The majority of unaccompanied children applying for permission to remain in the UK will be seeking asylum, and are therefore able to apply for legal aid. Legal aid also remains available for immigration advice for victims of trafficking and modern slavery, including child victims.</p><p> </p><p>Applications for non-asylum immigration cases involve the provision of factual information and accompanying evidence, so lawyers are not usually required.</p><p> </p><p>Civil legal aid has been retained for the highest priority cases, where life or liberty is at stake, where there is a risk of serious physical harm, loss of home, or where children may be removed from a family. Exceptional case funding may be available in non-asylum immigration cases.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-09-09T14:19:28.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391877/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391877/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-21","Legal Aid Scheme: Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will make it his policy to reinstate immigration legal aid funding for unaccompanied children.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","8200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391878","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-08","<p>Statistics on juvenile re-offending are published in the Proven Re-offending Statistics, which is released quarterly. The most recent statistics can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/proven-reoffending-statistics-quarterly-october-2012-to-september-2013" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/proven-reoffending-statistics-quarterly-october-2012-to-september-2013</a>.</p><p> </p><p>We are working hard to make sure young offenders have the skills and self-discipline they need to turn their lives around and stop offending.</p><p>Crime is falling and fewer young people are entering the criminal justice system, but those who are need the right support. That is why we have taken steps to improve education and training for young people while in custody and on release.</p><p> </p><p>A proven re-offence is defined as any offence committed in a one year follow-up period that leads to a court conviction or caution in the one year follow-up or within a further six month waiting period to allow the offence to be proven in court.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-09-08T09:10:41.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391878/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391878/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-21","Young Offenders: Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what his Department's latest estimate is of the number of juveniles who reoffend within a year of their release from custody.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","8201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391879","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-08","<p /> <p>The Ministry of Justice is funding the Restorative Justice Council to develop and manage quality standards for delivery of restorative justice in the criminal justice system and to raise the profile of restorative justice so that victims can make an informed decision on whether to participate.</p><p>Given that these projects are not providing direct restorative justice services, it is not possible to use them to assess the cost benefits of restorative justice.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-08T10:04:29.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391879/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391879/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-21","Reparation by Offenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the cost benefits of restorative justice through projects run by the Restorative Justice Council.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","8202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391880","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-07","<p /> <p>The consultation paper on the provision of court and tribunal estate in England and Wales will run for 12 weeks from 16 July 2015 until 8 October 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Any impact on staff arising as a result of these proposals are subject to the outcome of the consultation. No decisions will be made until every response has been considered carefully.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/proposal-on-the-provision-of-court-and-tribunal-es" target="_blank">https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/proposal-on-the-provision-of-court-and-tribunal-es</a></p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-09-07T13:57:49.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391880/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391880/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-21","Courts: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Written Statement of 16 July 2015 on HM Courts and Tribunals Service, HLWS108, what estimate he has made of job losses arising as a result of his proposals to reduce the cost of the court estate.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","8373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391881","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-07","<p>The consultation paper on the provision of court and tribunal estate in England and Wales will run for 12 weeks from 16 July 2015 until 8 October 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Costs for any future improvements which might be written off and any savings as a result of reducing the estate that might be re-invested are all subject to the outcome of the consultation. The consultation also asks for views on what types of alternative provision might be appropriate if any sites are closed, including whether civic and other public buildings could be used for hearings. No decisions will be made until every response has been considered carefully.</p><p> </p><p>Information on travel times is included in each regional consultation paper.</p><p><a href="https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/proposal-on-the-provision-of-court-and-tribunal-es" target="_blank">https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/proposal-on-the-provision-of-court-and-tribunal-es</a>. It will still be the case that over 95% of citizens will be able to reach their required court within an hour by car and the proportion able to reach a tribunal within an hour by car will remain unchanged at 83%.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","8369 ; 8370 ; 8371","2015-09-07T16:08:01.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391881/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391881/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-21","Courts: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Written Statement of 16 July 2015 on HM Courts and Tribunals Service, HLWS108, what assessment he has made of the time that would be required by citizens, under the proposed changes to the court estate, to reach their required court by public transport.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","8372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391882","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-20","<p>Three courts – Rhyl County Court, Abergavenny Magistrates’ Court and Caerphilly Magistrates’ Court – have previously been announced for closure and are yet to close. Any work undertaken on them has been necessary for the courts to function, such as essential maintenance and making the buildings suitable for disabled access. Resource maintenance and capital expenditure is in the attached table.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-10-20T10:56:43.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391882/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391882/answer","Maintenance & Improvement of Courts.xls","Maintenance & Improvement of Courts.xls","Cost of Maintenance & Improvement of Courts","Cost of Maintenance & Improvement of Courts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391882/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-21","Courts: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much his Department spent on maintenance or improvement of courts which have been scheduled to be closed in the last five years; and what costs were incurred in planning future improvements to those courts which will now be written off.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","8351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391883","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-07","<p>The consultation paper on the provision of court and tribunal estate in England and Wales will run for 12 weeks from 16 July 2015 until 8 October 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Costs for any future improvements which might be written off and any savings as a result of reducing the estate that might be re-invested are all subject to the outcome of the consultation. The consultation also asks for views on what types of alternative provision might be appropriate if any sites are closed, including whether civic and other public buildings could be used for hearings. No decisions will be made until every response has been considered carefully.</p><p> </p><p>Information on travel times is included in each regional consultation paper.</p><p><a href="https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/proposal-on-the-provision-of-court-and-tribunal-es" target="_blank">https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/proposal-on-the-provision-of-court-and-tribunal-es</a>. It will still be the case that over 95% of citizens will be able to reach their required court within an hour by car and the proportion able to reach a tribunal within an hour by car will remain unchanged at 83%.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","8369 ; 8371 ; 8372","2015-09-07T16:08:01.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391883/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391883/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-21","Courts: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Written Statement of 16 July 2015 on HM Courts and Tribunals Service, HLWS108, what costs incurred on future improvements to courts proposed for closure will now be written off.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","8370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391884","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-07","<p>The consultation paper on the provision of court and tribunal estate in England and Wales will run for 12 weeks from 16 July 2015 until 8 October 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Costs for any future improvements which might be written off and any savings as a result of reducing the estate that might be re-invested are all subject to the outcome of the consultation. The consultation also asks for views on what types of alternative provision might be appropriate if any sites are closed, including whether civic and other public buildings could be used for hearings. No decisions will be made until every response has been considered carefully.</p><p> </p><p>Information on travel times is included in each regional consultation paper.</p><p><a href="https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/proposal-on-the-provision-of-court-and-tribunal-es" target="_blank">https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/proposal-on-the-provision-of-court-and-tribunal-es</a>. It will still be the case that over 95% of citizens will be able to reach their required court within an hour by car and the proportion able to reach a tribunal within an hour by car will remain unchanged at 83%.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","8369 ; 8370 ; 8372","2015-09-07T16:08:01.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391884/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391884/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391884/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-21","Courts: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Written Statement of 16 July 2015 on HM Courts and Tribunals Service, HLWS108, what proportion of the savings made by reducing the cost of the court estate will be re-invested in that estate; and in what ways will it be re-invested.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","8371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391885","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-07","<p /> <p>The consultation paper on the provision of court and tribunal estate in England and Wales will run for 12 weeks from 16 July 2015 until 8 October 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Costs for any future improvements which might be written off and any savings as a result of reducing the estate that might be re-invested are all subject to the outcome of the consultation. The consultation also asks for views on what types of alternative provision might be appropriate if any sites are closed, including whether civic and other public buildings could be used for hearings. No decisions will be made until every response has been considered carefully.</p><p> </p><p>Information on travel times is included in each regional consultation paper.</p><p><a href="https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/proposal-on-the-provision-of-court-and-tribunal-es" target="_blank">https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/proposal-on-the-provision-of-court-and-tribunal-es</a>. It will still be the case that over 95% of citizens will be able to reach their required court within an hour by car and the proportion able to reach a tribunal within an hour by car will remain unchanged at 83%.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","8370 ; 8371 ; 8372","2015-09-07T16:08:01.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391885/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391885/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-21","Courts: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Written Statement of 16 July 2015 on HM Courts and Tribunals Service, what criteria will be used to determine which civic and other public buildings can be used for hearings.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","8369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391886","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-08","<p>Whipping is a matter for individual political parties and not a matter that the Government can comment on.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-09-08T15:50:08.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391886/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391886/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-21","Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will allow a free vote on any division in the House on the Government's proposed changes to Sunday trading regulations.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","8288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391887","Prime Minister","false","2015-09-07","<p>Ministers and officials engage widely with partners across government, academia, faith groups and communities as part of the process of policy development and delivery. This includes in the development of the new counter-extremism measures I announced in my speech of 20 July, and our comprehensive new counter-extremism strategy that will launch later this year.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron","8133","2015-09-07T15:44:03.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391887/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391887/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2015-07-21","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, which (a) Muslim and (b) non-governmental groups he consulted on the policies announced in his five-year counter-extremism strategy announced on 20 July 2015.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","8132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391888","Prime Minister","false","2015-09-07","<p>Ministers and officials engage widely with partners across government, academia, faith groups and communities as part of the process of policy development and delivery. This includes in the development of the new counter-extremism measures I announced in my speech of 20 July, and our comprehensive new counter-extremism strategy that will launch later this year.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron","8132","2015-09-07T15:44:03.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391888/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391888/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2015-07-21","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, which (a) Muslim and (b) other non-governmental groups he consulted on his counter-extremism speech made on 20 July 2015.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","8133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391889","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-10","<p>HM Revenue and Customs continues to provide proactive help and support for the smallest businesses and meets with small business representative groups regularly to hear their views, along with colleagues from HM Treasury. The European Commission has taken issues raised by the UK government into account in plans for further reform, published in the Commission’s Communication on the Digital Single Market on 6 May. These include a common EU-wide simplification measure (VAT threshold) to help small start-up e-commerce businesses.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-10T14:56:19.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391889/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391889/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Electronic Commerce: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 24 March 2015 to Question 228461, what steps he is taking to ensure that micro-businesses are not disadvantaged by Directive 2008/8/EC on EU VAT for digital services sold across borders; what progress he has made on getting the best deal for British firms; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","8355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391890","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-07","<p>Network Rail proposes to deliver electrification of the Barking to Gospel Oak line by summer 2017, in time for the new four-car electric trains ordered by TfL to be introduced in 2018. Network Rail is still assessing the detailed cost of the electrification and gauge enhancement scheme between Thameshaven/Tilbury Docks and the Midland Main Line via Barking and Gospel Oak and the forecast cost will be provided to DfT in due course.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-07T10:28:50.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391890/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391890/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","Gospel Oak-Barking Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what timetable is planned for the electrification of the Barking to Gospel Oak line; what forecast he has made of the cost of that electrification; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Corbyn","Islington North","Jeremy Corbyn","8322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391891","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-10","<p>Transport for the North (TfN) was formed out of the One North initiative.　TfN was established by the cities in the north for the people of the north to work in partnership with Government. Ministers and Officials have held discussions with a wide range of stakeholders, including those from outside of the UK, on the role of TfN.　However, it is not for Government to impose its will on the region, but to work with the region to drive economic growth.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-09-10T15:18:22.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391891/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391891/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","Transport: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he has had discussions with (a) Transport for London and (b) transport authorities in other countries on establishing Transport for the North.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","8146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391892","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-07","<p>The projects in addition to the agreed Rail Investment Strategy are:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Project</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Funding (m)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ely-Soham double tracking</p></td><td><p>35.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Syston – Stoke gauge enhancement</p></td><td><p>20.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sheffield Tram Train</p></td><td><p>48.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>New Stations Fund (5 stations)</p></td><td><p>19.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Windermere electrification</p></td><td><p>16.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Western flood resistance</p></td><td><p>26.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hull electrification study</p></td><td><p>2.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Coventry – Nuneaton Phase 2</p></td><td><p>5.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wigan – Bolton electrification</p></td><td><p>37.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Gospel Oak – Barking and London freight electrification</p></td><td><p>90.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Gatwick station (second phase)</p></td><td><p>20.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Chesterton Station</p></td><td><p>44.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Access for All ‘top-up’</p></td><td><p>60.0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The project funding is not broken down by year as Network Rail was reclassified to the public sector, which means that project funding spend is triggered by the projects’ actual expenditure in each year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There is a small variation between the total funding amounts in this table and the one sent earlier under the heading “Funding for projects in addition to the agreed Rail Investment Strategy”. This is because the table in question 5694 is a cash forecast year by year, whereas this table is the price set at the projects’ earlier approval dates.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-07T10:39:54.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391892/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391892/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2015 to Question 6967, what funding has been allocated to each project for each year under the heading, Funding for projects in addition to the agreed Rail Investment Strategy, given in the Answer of 9 July 2015 to Question 5694.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","8163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391893","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Department worked with both Northern and Transpennine Express (TPE) to develop a scheme to provide additional capacity in North-west England, which includes the use of the locomotives – and coaches – on the Cumbrian Coast line. The rolling stock provider, DRS, has chosen to use Class 37 locomotives. These trains provide additional capacity on this popular route and a new early morning service from Carlisle to Sellafield and Barrow-in-Furness. The project has enabled capacity to be increased on many TPE train services between Blackpool and Manchester.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-09-11T09:02:54.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391893/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391893/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","Rolling Stock: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions his Department had with Northern Rail on the use of the Class 37 rolling stock on the Carlisle-Barrow-Lancaster rail line.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","8127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391894","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-11","<p>There are no likely effects from pausing electrification of the TransPennine rail route to the planned upgrades to the Midland Mainline and therefore no contingency plans are required.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-09-11T08:38:34.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391894/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391894/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","Midland Main Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the likely effect of the delayed electrification of the TransPennine rail route to planned upgrades to the Midland Mainline; and what contingency plans he has put in place to mitigate such effects.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","8170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391895","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-10","<p>Highways England is currently designing safety schemes to improve safety at both roundabouts at either end of the Ilminster By-pass. The Road Investment Strategy also announced, in addition to the schemes on the A303 to be taken forward in the period up to 2020/21, the Government’s intention to up-grade the A303 in subsequent road investment periods, post-2020, which will include the up-grade of the Ilminster By-pass to a dual carriageway, which will aim to further improve safety.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>I do however offer my deepest sympathies to the families and friends of the people who lost their lives or were seriously injured in the collisions on the Ilminster By-pass in July 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These collisions are still under Police investigation and until concluded it would be inappropriate to speculate on causes and subsequent improvements to that stretch of road. It is important to base decisions on evidence and Highways England will work with partner agencies to further reduce casualties on our roads in light of the evidence as it emerges.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-09-10T15:14:22.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391895/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391895/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","A303: Bypasses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to improve the safety of the Ilminster bypass on the A303; and if he will direct the Highways Agency to revisit this matter in the light of recent serious accidents on that road.","false","Biography information for Mr Marcus Fysh","Yeovil","Marcus Fysh","8207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391896","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-07","<p>Network Rail is carrying out the work to improve the Walsall to Rugeley Trent Valley Line. They have advised that £27.3m has been incurred so far on the project to electrify the line. Work carried out to date has included the structures clearance work, detailed design of the electrification system, and the contract award to ABC Electrification, the main contractor.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The route clearance work is substantially complete and has gone well. This has involved 5 bridges being reconstructed, and 11 track lowerings being undertaken. The remaining significant civil engineering work is to lift the headroom in Park St Tunnel, Walsall, which is scheduled to be carried out from October 2015 to May 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>An interfacing scheme (journey time improvement between Ryecroft and Rugeley) is currently in the detailed design phase.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-07T10:26:54.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391896/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391896/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","Walsall-Rugeley Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what (a) work has been carried out and (b) expenditure has been made on work to electrify and upgrade the Chase Line from Walsall to Rugeley Trent Valley to date.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","8229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391897","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-07","<p>The electrification of the Chase Line from Walsall to Rugeley Trent Valley is continuing and is scheduled to be completed by December 2017.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-07T10:38:09.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391897/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391897/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","Walsall-Rugeley Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether electrification of the Chase Line from Walsall to Rugeley Trent Valley is included in the projects paused as part of the assessment of the High Level Output Specification.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","8230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391898","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-07","<p>No projects are being cancelled. The Secretary of State has asked Sir Peter Hendy to put forward proposals for re-planning the CP5 investment programme to ensure it can be delivered effectively and efficiently.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-07T10:44:42.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391898/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391898/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391898/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 16 July 2015 to Question 6793, whether he has seen or requested a copy of the list of projects that would be stopped or refused which was referred to on page 3 of Network Rail's Board minutes of 25 November 2014.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","8231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391899","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-10","<p>In 2012, following a call for evidence to explore the options for the future of the government’s 49% shareholding in NATS, the government announced that it planned to retain its share in NATS Holdings. However, as with all government held assets, the government continues to keep ownership options under review.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","8267","2015-09-10T13:50:04.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391899/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391899/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391899/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","National Air Traffic Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his Department policy is on retaining the Government's stake in National Air Traffic Service Holdings; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","8268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391900","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-10","<p>In 2012, following a call for evidence to explore the options for the future of the government’s 49% shareholding in NATS, the government announced that it planned to retain its share in NATS Holdings. However, as with all government held assets, the government continues to keep ownership options under review.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","8268","2015-09-10T13:50:04.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391900/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391900/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","National Air Traffic Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether an official in his Department has examined the feasibility of (a) partially and (b) wholly selling his Department's share of National Air Traffic Service Holdings.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","8267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391901","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-07","<p>Her Majesty’s Coastguard has undertaken an in depth analysis of its historical incident data to develop suggested staffing levels for the National Network by time of day (day or night) and season (low, medium, high and peak). During the current transition period this level has also depended on the geographical scope of the National Network as areas previously managed by Maritime Rescue Coordination Centres migrate into it.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Between January and July 2015 the National Network was staffed at the suggested levels on 93% of occasions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>On occasions where staffing is below these levels the flexibility of the National Network allows for support to be made available to teams experiencing very high workloads from teams elsewhere in the network with spare capacity.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-09-07T10:36:40.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391901/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391901/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391901/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","HM Coastguard: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what metric his Department uses to assess the risk-assessed level of staffing at coastguard operations centres; and what assessment he has made of those risk-assessed staffing levels using this metric at each of the coastguard operations centres in the period from January 2015 to July 2015.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","8374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391902","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-07","<p>As at 21 July 2015 61 out of the 75 Coastguards (81%) appointed to roles at the National Maritime Operations Centre (NMOC) in Fareham had attained the qualification level required for the Centre to reach full operational capacity by December 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Recruitment and training for the NMOC and wider National Network is phased incrementally to deliver the right number of Coastguards at the right point in the transition timetable. The new National Network progressively became operational from September 2014; transition will complete by the end of December 2015.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-09-07T10:25:23.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391902/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391902/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391902/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","HM Coastguard: Fareham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of staff at the National Maritime Operation Centre at Fareham had attained the qualification level required for the Centre to reach full operational capacity by December 2015 by 21 July 2015.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","8376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391903","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-07","<p>As at 2 July 2015, 75 out of the full complement of 96 Coastguards (78%) had been appointed to roles at the National Maritime Operations Centre (NMOC) in Fareham.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Recruitment for the NMOC and the wider National Network is phased incrementally to deliver the right number of Coastguards at the right point in the transition timetable. The new National Network progressively became operational from September 2014; transition will complete by the end of December 2015.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-09-07T10:43:13.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391903/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391903/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391903/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","HM Coastguard: Fareham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of the staff required for the National Maritime Operation Centre in Fareham to reach full operational capacity by December 2015 had been appointed by 2 July 2015.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","8375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391904","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Secretary of State was first advised to pause major projects in June 2015, to allow the programme to be reset pending the outcome of Sir Peter Hendy’s review.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-09-07T10:35:01.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391904/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391904/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391904/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2015 to Question 7273, when he was first advised that a decision on whether to pause major projects may have to be taken.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","8317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391905","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) lead on airspace change and the process is set out in their publication CAP 725. The Department for Transport provide guidance to the CAA relating to the exercise of its air navigation functions. This sets out the Government’s position on flights over densely populated and tranquil areas. Any review of these publications would consider points made in consultation.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-09-11T11:54:53.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391905/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391905/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391905/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-21","Aviation: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking as part of his Department's current review of noise policy to ensure that (a) tranquillity and (b) densely populated areas are clearly defined in Civil Aviation Authority guidance.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","8293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391906","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Equality Act 2010 protects all individuals, including Gypsies and Travellers, against racial and other forms of discrimination. The Department will continue to work with colleagues across government to deliver the conditions for everyone to live and work successfully alongside each other, creating a more integrated community.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-09-07T10:24:06.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391906/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391906/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391906/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-21","Travellers: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what work the Government is doing to tackle discrimination against the Gypsy and Traveller communities.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","8256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391907","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Government recognises the commitment and value of parents who choose to stay at home to look after their children, and the difficulties they might face. The Government has introduced the Marriage Allowance which will benefit married parents who do not use their full personal allowance; it has made reforms to the state pension which will improve pension provision for those who choose not to work due to caring responsibilities; and introduced a new package of childcare support to help parents balance work and family life.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-09-07T14:53:57.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391907/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391907/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391907/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-21","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of recent changes to tax and tax credits on the income of women who choose to stay at home to care for children.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","8240"
